* Phillips to Sotheby=E2=80=99s: Hold my beer!: On Wednesday, Phillips anno=
unced that C.E.O. Edward Dolman was stepping down in favor of the company=
=E2=80=99s chief legal officer, Martin Wilson=E2=80=94the latest in a serie=
s of executive changes at the auction house. In recent years, Phillips has =
made strides as a specialty house that excels at making markets for the wor=
k of emerging artists and selling select high-value property. But to truly =
compete against Christie=E2=80=99s and Sotheby=E2=80=99s for the big
estates, Phillips needs a bigger balance sheet. Hence, there were persisten=
t rumors, several years back, that Phillips was looking for a buyer=E2=80=
=94until it wasn=E2=80=99t. By all accounts, the owner, Russian luxury-mall=
-and-real-estate developer The Mercury Group, had been offered a good price=
 for the firm. Ultimately, it decided not to sell.

Dolman, who is 64, had been making it clear for some time that he=E2=80=99d=
 had enough of running a business day to day. He became a C.E.O. at 39=E2=
=80=94and has run three
different institutions in the 25 years since. In 2021, he hired the widely =
liked Stephen Brooks, a former Christie=E2=80=99s chief operating officer, =
as C.E.O. to replace him; but Brooks left earlier this year. Dolman then tr=
ied another tack (he=E2=80=99s a sailor), promoting the also widely liked A=
manda Lo Iacono into the new role of deputy C.E.O. But Lo Iacono has decide=
d she=E2=80=99s had enough as well. Now, Dolman has set a date in May for h=
is departure, and Wilson
(another well-liked Christie=E2=80=99s veteran who is also involved in all =
of the company=E2=80=99s deals) is stepping in. What makes the management c=
hurn and succession confusion so surprising is Phillips=E2=80=99 reputation=
 as the nice-guy, no-drama auction house. It would be a shame to see that c=
hange.
* Sebastian Fahey to depart Sotheby=E2=80=99s: Among the several announceme=
nts that dropped last week, Sotheby=E2=80=99s informed staff that the manag=
ing director of the Global
Fine Art division, Sebastian Fahey, would be leaving the company. Fahey, th=
e highest-ranking cut announced thus far, had worked for Sotheby=E2=80=99s =
for 20 years=E2=80=94in London, Hong Kong, and, most recently, New York. In=
 an email, the company said it would be =E2=80=9Crevisiting the overall org=
anizational structure of GFA=E2=80=9D and =E2=80=9Csharing a new org design=
 and reporting lines in January.=E2=80=9D I=E2=80=99m told that Fahey may h=
ave had as many as 28 direct reports after the departure of GFA head Brooke
Lampley earlier this year.
* That=E2=80=99s half a million per commandment: Sotheby=E2=80=99s ended th=
e year with a banging $5 million sale of a stone tablet that is purported t=
o be a =E2=80=9Ccopy=E2=80=9D of the Ten Commandments. The object was purch=
ased eight years ago for $850,000 and will now, according to Sotheby=E2=80=
=99s, be donated to a museum in Israel. The New York Times is having none o=
f it. A week
before ( https://www.nytimes.com/2024/12/18/us/sothebys-ten-commandments-ta=
blet.html?utm_campaign=3DWall+Power+-+SUBSCRIBERS+%2812%2F22%2F24%29&utm_co=
ntent=3DWall+Power+-+SUBSCRIBERS+%2812%2F22%2F24%29&utm_medium=3Demail_acti=
on&utm_source=3Dcustomer.io&utm_term=3Df6c60617da42abd12a ) the sale, the n=
ewspaper contacted two scholars who provided a long list of reasons to doub=
t the stone=E2=80=99s origins and authenticity. Basically, since the object=
 was not found on an archaeological site, which would have properly documen=
ted its discovery, and because much of its lore is impossible to independen=
tly verify=E2=80=94there=E2=80=99s no carbon dating on stone,
and the best argument for the object is the alphabet used for the inscripti=
on=E2=80=94the Times issued a prominent caveat emptor ( https://www.nytimes=
=2Ecom/2024/12/12/arts/ten-commandments=
-stone-tablet-sothebys-auction.html?ut=
m_campaign=3DWall+Power+-+SUBSCRIBERS+%2812%2F22%2F24%29&utm_content=3DWall=
+Power+-+SUBSCRIBERS+%2812%2F22%2F24%29&utm_medium=3Demail_action&utm_sourc=
e=3Dcustomer.io&utm_term=3Df6c60617da42abd12a ).=C2=A0

When its warnings were not heeded, the paper followed up with an even stron=
ger consumer report, quoting the two scholars from the original article, an=
d adding a third who warned that =E2=80=9Cdoubts about the
tablet =E2=80=98should be taken seriously.=E2=80=99=E2=80=9D This is one of=
