Christie=E2=80=99s Response
---------------------

I happened to be speaking to another auction veteran at the very
moment Sotheby=E2=80=99s email started hitting inboxes. Surprisingly, the v=
eteran initially expressed disappointment that Christie=E2=80=99s C.E.O. Gu=
illaume Cerutti had done nothing to support Sotheby=E2=80=99s in reshaping =
the auction house revenue structure. The auction business is in a real bind=
, the veteran explained. Something has to change, and piling on more buyer=
=E2=80=99s premium, only to give it away to consignors in a brutally compet=
itive marketplace for acquiring property, is a path leading toward
self-destruction.=C2=A0

=C2=A0

Of course, the auction houses are precluded from coordinating their pricing=
 with the competition. It=E2=80=99s illegal; and, within living memory for =
employees at both houses, the late Alfred Taubman, who bought Sotheby=E2=80=
=99s in 1983 and eventually took it public, went to federal prison for a ye=
ar simply for opening the door to collusion. That said, the auction houses
have ways to signal their intentions that are legal and above board. The pr=
oblem, the auction veteran admitted, was that Sotheby=E2=80=99s came in wit=
h a =E2=80=9Chard opening bid.=E2=80=9D

=C2=A0

Its rival seems to have felt the same way. I was told by someone familiar w=
ith the thinking at the top of Christie=E2=80=99s that, in their view, Soth=
eby=E2=80=99s tried to do too much: re-establish the vendor=E2=80=99s commi=
ssion; end enhanced hammer deals below $50 million; and
lower the buyer=E2=80=99s premium to 20 percent=E2=80=94too quickly. As I m=
entioned ( https://puck.news/sothebys-debt-soap-opera/?utm_campaign=3DWall+=
