24px 0;"><em>Phillips to Sotheby=E2=80=99s: Hold my beer!</em>: On Wednesda=
y, Phillips announced that C.E.O. Edward Dolman was stepping down in favor =
of the company=E2=80=99s chief legal officer, Martin Wilson=E2=80=94the lat=
est in a series of executive changes at the auction house. In recent years,=
 Phillips has made strides as a specialty house that excels at making marke=
ts for the work of emerging artists and selling select high-value property.=
 But to truly compete against Christie=E2=80=99s and Sotheby=E2=80=99s for =
the big
estates, Phillips needs a bigger balance sheet. Hence, there were persisten=
t rumors, several years back, that Phillips was looking for a buyer=E2=80=
=94until it wasn=E2=80=99t. By all accounts, the owner, Russian luxury-mall=
-and-real-estate developer The Mercury Group, had been offered a good price=
 for the firm. Ultimately, it decided not to sell.<br/><br/>Dolman, who is =
64, had been making it clear for some time that he=E2=80=99d had enough of =
running a business day to day. He became a C.E.O. at 39=E2=80=94and has run=
 three
different institutions in the 25 years since. In 2021, he hired the widely =
liked <strong>Stephen Brooks</strong>, a former Christie=E2=80=99s chief op=
erating officer, as C.E.O. to replace him; but Brooks left earlier this yea=
r. Dolman then tried another tack (he=E2=80=99s a sailor), promoting the <e=
m>also </em>widely liked <strong>Amanda Lo Iacono</strong> into the new rol=
e of deputy C.E.O. But Lo Iacono has decided she=E2=80=99s had enough as we=
ll. Now, Dolman has set a date in May for his departure, and Wilson
(another well-liked Christie=E2=80=99s veteran who is also involved in all =
of the company=E2=80=99s deals) is stepping in. What makes the management c=
hurn and succession confusion so surprising is Phillips=E2=80=99 reputation=
 as the nice-guy, no-drama auction house. It would be a shame to see that c=
hange.=C2=A0</li><li style=3D"Margin:0 0 24px 0;"><em>Sebastian Fahey to de=
part Sotheby=E2=80=99s</em>: Among the several announcements that dropped l=
ast week, Sotheby=E2=80=99s informed staff that the managing director of th=
e Global
Fine Art division, <strong>Sebastian Fahey</strong>, would be leaving the c=
ompany. Fahey, the highest-ranking cut announced thus far, had worked for S=
otheby=E2=80=99s for 20 years=E2=80=94in London, Hong Kong, and, most recen=
tly, New York. In an email, the company said it would be =E2=80=9Crevisitin=
g the overall organizational structure of GFA=E2=80=9D and =E2=80=9Csharing=
 a new org design and reporting lines in January.=E2=80=9D I=E2=80=99m told=
 that Fahey may have had as many as 28 direct reports after the departure o=
f GFA head <strong>Brooke
Lampley</strong> earlier this year.=C2=A0</li><li aria-level=3D"1" style=3D=
"Margin:0 0 24px 0;"><em>That=E2=80=99s half a million per commandment</em>=
: Sotheby=E2=80=99s ended the year with a banging $5 million sale of a ston=
e tablet that is purported to be a =E2=80=9Ccopy=E2=80=9D of the Ten Comman=
dments. The object was purchased eight years ago for $850,000 and will now,=
 according to Sotheby=E2=80=99s, be donated to a museum in Israel. <em>The =
New York Times</em> is having none of it. A week
<a href=3D"https://email.puck.news/e/c/eyJlbWFpbF9pZCI6ImRnVDJ4Z1lEQUt2Uktx=
