=3D"margin:0;margin-bottom:0px;">=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin:0;margin-bott=
om:0px;">And so, last week, Sotheby=E2=80=99s announced internally that it =
will be =E2=80=9Creintroducing selective flexibility
on seller=E2=80=99s financial terms=E2=80=9D in February, which means every=
thing is up for negotiation if you=E2=80=99ve got the goods. Externally, th=
e house set the new fee structure at 27 percent on purchases up to $1 milli=
on; 22 percent from $1 million to $8 million; and 15 percent thereafter. (C=
hristie=E2=80=99s charges 26 percent up to $1 million; 21 percent to $6 mil=
lion; and 15 percent thereafter; Phillips=E2=80=99 fees are 27 percent to $=
1 million; 21 percent to $6 million; 14.5 percent thereafter.) Yes, you rea=
d that right:
Sotheby=E2=80=99s raised its fees above its competitors=E2=80=99.=C2=A0</p>=
<p style=3D"margin:0;margin-bottom:0px;">=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin:0;">I=
t=E2=80=99s a smart move by Sotheby=E2=80=99s to cut its losses and raise i=
ts rates, which gives them more negotiating room against Christie=E2=80=99s=
 to regain selling position in the new year. One European collector I know =
described the rate change email, which arrived after the company endured a =
traumatic week of layoffs while an absent Stewart was bragging on Instagram=
 about his trip to
Abu Dhabi, as a =E2=80=9CP.R. clusterfuck.=E2=80=9D I get that. But I don=
=E2=80=99t fully understand why Sotheby=E2=80=99s isn=E2=80=99t making a <e=
m>virtue</em> of this wholesale restructuring of the company by giving the =
layoffs some time to breathe and then announcing the new fees at the beginn=
ing of the new year, so they can mark a fresh start. Clearly, leadership se=
es the about-face as a black eye rather than something to celebrate.=C2=A0<=
/p></div>
