eries of measured moves that Christie=E2=80=99s and Phillips could have res=
ponded to, building trust and cooperation over time. Instead, they went all=
 in, but didn=E2=80=99t have the cards to back it up. By all internal accou=
nts, Stewart
had been blithely confident that Christie=E2=80=99s would follow his lead o=
n fees=E2=80=94a failure to read his opponent that only compounded the prob=
lem.</p><p style=3D"margin:0;margin-bottom:0px;">=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"marg=
in:0;margin-bottom:0px;">Cerutti, for his part, is widely known to be hyper=
-competitive. Folks at Sotheby=E2=80=99s complain, with some justification,=
 that he has targeted some of their consignments=E2=80=94notably, works by =
<strong>Willem de Kooning</strong> and <strong>Joan Mitchell=E2=80=94</stro=
ng>with gratuitous
counterprogramming. But presented with so many ways to press an advantage o=
ver his rivals, there was little chance Cerutti was going to level the play=
ing field entirely.=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin:0;margin-bottom:0px;">=C2=
=A0</p><p style=3D"margin:0;">Sotheby=E2=80=99s moved so far, so fast, that=
 Cerutti was able to improve his <em>own</em> negotiating position with con=
signors while still maintaining an edge over his rivals across town. It wou=
ld have been hard for him not to do it. The situation brings to
mind a quote attributed to McDonald=E2=80=99s genius <strong>Ray Kroc</stro=
ng>. =E2=80=9CIf my competitor were drowning,=E2=80=9D Kroc supposedly said=
=E2=80=94and I=E2=80=99ve heard more than a few C.E.O.s repeat this quote=
=E2=80=94=E2=80=9CI=E2=80=99d walk over and put a hose right in his mouth.=
